<topic id="28607cc6-92e6-4585-85ac-d080e489a9a6" revisionNumber="0">
  <developerConceptualDocument xmlns="http://ddue.schemas.microsoft.com/authoring/2003/5" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
    <introduction>
      <para>
        This section contains articles that relay important and useful information for developers
        wishing to work with SlimDX. Reading them will give insight on design choices taken
        for the library's development, and will help ensure that it is used correctly and efficiently.
      </para>
    </introduction>

    <section>
      <title>Programming Guide</title>
      
      <content>
        <para>
          This guide is divided into the following sections:
        </para>
        <list class="bullet">
          <listItem>
            <para>
              <link xlink:href="10407d29-3a6c-49cc-8c77-e96cd4659780">Getting Started</link>
              - This section explains the basics of how to get started with SlimDX.
            </para>
          </listItem>
          <listItem>
            <para>
              <link xlink:href="531e076b-ade0-47f3-b11b-b75a426f94e8">Debugging Tips</link>
              - Contains useful tips and pointers on how to debug problems in your SlimDX application.
            </para>
          </listItem>
          <listItem>
            <para>
              <link xlink:href="598b267f-52e6-4adb-906b-879c0bc8c736">Object Lifetimes</link>
              - This section discusses the mechanics behind construction, disposal, and destruction of objects in SlimDX.
            </para>
          </listItem>
          <listItem>
            <para>
              <link xlink:href="1db9c09e-396b-4631-b48e-2e5b4895c49b">Handling 32 and 64 Bit Targets</link>
              - This section covers how to correctly configure a SlimDX application to run properly on both 32 bit and 64 bit systems.
            </para>
          </listItem>
          <listItem>
            <para>
              <link xlink:href="443ed878-a18a-4ddc-ac88-c0f124ff0495">Managed Message Loop</link>
              - Explains the rationale behind the canonical message loop in SlimDX projects.
            </para>
          </listItem>
        </list>
      </content>
    </section>

  </developerConceptualDocument>
</topic>